Giving up was never an option for me! 

I had plenty of opportunities to give up but I never did:

👉🏼 When my father drowned when I was 3 years old

👉🏼 When I knew my mother had severe mental illness

👉🏼 When I was emancipated at 15 years old

👉🏼 When I became a single mother at 22 years old

👉🏼 When a recession hit soon after launching my first company 

Giving up is simply not in my DNA. 

Ever since I was on my own, I’ve never had a Plan B. When you have other options, there IS an option for failure!

The only option I had was to be successful one way or the other.

Keep pushing ahead. You’re more powerful than you could ever imagine. 👊🏼

DON’T quit ! YOU got this 💪

 #resilience #dontgiveup #dontquit #leadership

“I completely blew it!” 

We’ve all had these moments, right?
It’s NOTHING to be ashamed of. 😬

To me, failing fast and failing forward is one of the best and most significant ways to gain experience and promote growth. 💪🏼

How do you view failure?

Do you view it as…
… a very significant character flaw?
… an opportunity for growth?
… an opportunity to understand your weaknesses and develop? 

Talk to Me 

Let me know in the comments below! 👇🏼

#growth #opportunity #failure #leadership #accountability #personaldevelopment

The word "Quit" is not in my vocabulary. 

And it never will be!

I'm a fighter. 🥊

I have always been a fighter and a little bit stubborn. 

Even as a little girl, I was determined to do things my way and nothing was going to stop me from doing just that. Tell me “no” or “I can’t” then just wait and see! 😬

You might say that this is what has gotten me where I am today: an entrepreneur who has built her own businesses from scratch, creating something out of nothing.

In fact, my life has been filled with so many challenges that sometimes it seems like they're coming at me from all directions! 

But each time one comes at me, instead of turning away or giving up, I step right up and say

“BRING IT ON!" 

Then I do whatever it takes to get through it.

Life is about accepting the challenges along the way, and choosing to keep moving forward!

Talk to me in the comments below 👇🏾

What was the biggest challenge that you've had to overcomer? 

#resilience #dontquit #dontgiveup #fighter #leadership

Let’s Be Real!  Let’s Be HONEST! Let’s Be Succinct!

This CAN be a struggle with a new client but something that is ABSOLUTELY vital to talk about.

Let’s say you do discovery and based on all of the information provided to you in your interview you decide this is someone you can help get to THEIR next level. 

Let’s say you are now fully engaged, yet the scope continues to change from the initial agreement of services. All while you are finding out new and critically important information daily.

Let’s say you are finding some of the reasons for the engagement are not necessarily truthful or that the client truly believed they were in a completely different position than they really are. 

What now? How does a professional handle this?

The first thing I do is ensure we are using the exact same dictionary. Ask hard questions! Follow up with a paper trail.

Client may say…👇🏼

“I want to make a lot of money.” 💰
Okay, what is a lot of money to you? 

“I want financial freedom.” 🙌🏻
What does this mean to you?

“I don’t want to be tied to an office.” 😓
Does this mean you don’t want to be stuck in the state or that you want to work remotely?

I ask A LOT of strong clarifying questions, then follow with a kind email or letter reflecting on the new plan!

One thing I do often is teach my clients how to pivot and redefine scope with measurements of success. 

To do this effectively, one of the biggest and most significant things is ensuring the dictionary between you and your client is identical. 

Everyone needs to be on the same page. 

How do you encourage your clients to define and utilize the same dictionary as you?

 🚨Tell me in the comments below 👇🏾

“Fix this or else!” 

Circling items on a sheet of paper in bright red with a ‘fix this or else’ attitude 
❌ WRONG WAY. 

Holding people to high standards but not providing the training or development to help them achieve it. 
❌ WRONG WAY

Making managers accountable and having the development of their talent be a priority.
✅ RIGHT WAY 

As a consultant, most of the time I’m on the outside looking in.
 
It’s easy to see many things that most insiders are blind to. 

Working as a performance coach and business consultant there have been many problems I have solutioned quickly given my view from the outside. 

However; most of the challenges were not platform, software, or hardware related. 

They were human.
They were soft skills.
They were lack of care or concern.

Understanding the journey is a key factor in solving:

❌ Low EQ
❌ Lack of  Self-Awareness
❌ Inadequate Training
❌ Toxicity Among The Team

So many corporate surveys find accountability is a HUGE driver in employee engagement and disengagement. 
Real performance accountability with effective feedback and coaching enables people to meet or exceed expectations you have for them. 

The goal is to maximize accountability. 
⬇️
Increase employee engagement.
⬇️
Increase business results.

Talk to me: Agree ? What do you think businesses should focus on from the inside ?

Never make the same mistake TWICE

This short sentence will help you go a long way 👆

When you make a mistake for the first time
👉You LEARN

But

If you don’t implement your learning, 
And make the same mistake again
👉That’s NEGLIGENCE

So

If you are a business owner or a leader of any sort-

✅Learn from your mistakes

✅Identify what went wrong

✅Change to prevent it from happening again

AND…. For the love!!! ADMIT WHEN YOUR WRONG!

You can’t prevent a future crisis if you don’t change:

➤The Behavior #change 

➤The Processes

➤The Habits

All of it …. 

Talk to me in the comments below 👇🏾

What is your process following a mistake or failure to ensure it doesn’t happen again ?

 #mistakes #failure #growth #leadership

A great leader is like a gladiator.

They know how to fight, how to win, how to develop their #TEAM

They know how to keep their head in the game.

They have the confidence AND grace that comes from knowing they can succeed. 

They are focused, disciplined, and resilient.

All #like  traits of all great leaders.

But what makes a great leader great? 

It's not just about having those qualities; it's about using them when it matters most. The HARD times.

It's about putting yourself on the line for something bigger than yourself, a cause that inspires you and others around you to be better versions of themselves.

That's what makes a leader truly great: not just the ability to lead, but the ability to inspire others through their own actions.

Will it be easy?

No 

Worth it?

Absolutely!

Talk to me in the comments below ! 👇🏾

Who do you know who is a great leader? 

 #leaders #leadership #inspiration #team
